The massive corpus of dark-web data collected by the Dutch led to a series of high-profile busts. The FBI executed more than 240 arrests, seized 1,700 lbs. of drugs, and $13.5 million in cash and cryptocurrency. But was it enough? 9/15

The carefully coordinated agitprop sent an all-pervading sense of paranoia rippling across the dark web. It was warranted. While running Hansa, the Dutch had collected data on a staggering 420,000 users including 10,000 home addresses. 8/15 https://t.co/b0nsOTtRm2

When the time came to reveal the ruse, the Dutch and US governments simultaneously announced their coordinated action against both Alphabay and Hansa. ‚ÄúYou are not safe. You cannot hide,‚Äù said US attorney general Jeff Sessions. 7/15 https://t.co/MAZTmVpoir

Those ‚Äúevil plans‚Äù included tricking drug dealers into uploading identifying information, downloading malware that revealed their locations, and receiving adorable stuffed panda bears in the mail‚Äîwith GPS trackers hidden inside. 6/15

As the moment to reveal their surveillance coup drew closer, the Dutch police grew more brazen. They held ‚Äúevil plan‚Äù meetings to brainstorm devious schemes to track and identify ever more unwitting Hansa users. 5/15

But when a news leak confirmed the takedown of Alphabay and Cazes‚Äô death, the Dutch knew their undercover surveillance operation couldn‚Äôt go on indefinitely. The moment was approaching to take off their masks. 4/15 https://t.co/h6Q16Twmjb
